Detailed Parts of the Plant
click on each part for details
Shoot A shoot is the whole of a stem, together with all the parts that are attached to it, such as a leaf or flower. Shoot
Flower Bud A flower bud is the sign that a flower is about to bloom. Once the flower is open, its bright colors attract insects for pollination. Flower Bud
Leaf A plants leaves collect energy from the sun and make food for the using a process called photosynthesis. Leaf
Leaf Stalk A slender leaf stalk attaches the leaf of the plants stem. Leaf Stalk
Stem A plants stem transports water through the plant. It also raises the height of the plants flowers and leaves and brings them closer to the Sun. Stem
Small Shoot Small shoots that sprout around the base of larger plants are called suckers. Small Shoot
Main Root Many plants have a main root that divides to anchor the plant to the ground. It keeps the plant steady and upright. Main Root
Secondary Roots Secondary, or lateral, roots grow out from the main root. Secondary Roots
Root Hairs Fine root hairs near the tip of each root take in, or absorb, water and minerals from the soil. Root Hairs
